<CLR_EXEC>.llm_response: The image you are seeing is part of a sensor anomaly detection system. The first image shows a sensor component, and the second image provides an explanation using the Integrated Gradients technique. This technique highlights the important features that the AI system considers when making its prediction. The left side of the second image shows the original sensor image, while the right side visualizes the attributions for the class "OK," indicating which parts of the image were most influential in the AI's decision. In the ISee Platform, we have several explainers that can be used to understand image-based predictions. For instance, the Integrated Gradients technique is similar to the '/Images/GradientInput' explainer, which computes attributions by taking the partial derivatives of the output with respect to the input and multiplying them with the input itself. This method helps in improving the sharpness of the attribution maps. Additionally, other explainers like '/Images/SmoothGrad' and '/Images/VarGrad' offer gradient-based explanations by averaging the gradient or its variance at several points, which helps in reducing visual noise and improving the clarity of explanations. These explainers are available on the ISee Platform, and users can try them out to gain deeper insights into their AI models.
